Compare any Strong/Very Strong Blue fluorescence stone in the same search against these None benchmarks to calculate your actual discount before purchasing.

## Frequently Asked Questions

### Does Blue fluorescence make a diamond look blue?

Under normal indoor LED lighting: no. The fluorescence is not activated. Under UV-rich daylight or black lights: a Strong Blue stone will glow a soft to vivid blue, which for most diamonds appears as added brightness rather than a blue tint. In Very Strong stones, the blue glow can appear distinctly blue-white. Under standard jewellery store lighting (mix of halogen and fluorescent): Faint and Medium Blue stones show no visible effect; Strong Blue may show slight added brightness.

### Will I notice a difference between a None and Faint Blue fluorescence diamond?

In virtually all real-world settings: no. Faint Blue fluorescence is essentially invisible under normal indoor lighting and barely perceptible even under direct UV light. The visual difference between None and Faint is below the threshold of casual observation in any normal ring-wearing scenario. Faint fluorescence is the risk-free discount tier.

### Is fluorescence a clarity issue or a cut issue?

Neither. Fluorescence is an independent characteristic graded separately from the 4Cs on the GIA report. It has no relationship to cut proportions, clarity inclusions, colour body tint, or surface polish. It is caused by structural characteristics in the diamond's crystal growth that are unrelated to how the stone was cut or what inclusions it contains.

### Why does the diamond industry discount fluorescence if it's often invisible?

Historical stigma established in the wholesale market. Earlier diamond grading standards and some historical GIA studies identified that in extreme cases, Very Strong fluorescence could cause haziness — and the market responded by broadly discounting all fluorescent diamonds, even Faint and Medium grades where the risk is negligible. This creates the pricing anomaly that savvy buyers can exploit: Faint and Medium Blue stones are discounted based on category association with a risk that only affects a small percentage of Very Strong stones.

### Does lab-grown diamond fluorescence work the same way as natural diamond fluorescence?

Lab-grown diamonds can exhibit fluorescence, but the prevalence and causes differ from natural diamonds. CVD-grown lab diamonds sometimes show orange fluorescence (undesirable); HPHT-grown lab diamonds more commonly show blue fluorescence similar to natural diamonds. The visual and pricing rules are similar: blue fluorescence can cause haze in Very Strong grades; the video check applies. Check the fluorescence grade on the certificate for any lab stone and apply the same video verification protocol.

### Can I use fluorescence to help choose between two otherwise identical stones?

Yes, and this is exactly the intended application. If two stones both pass the 12-point proportion and certificate audit, and one is None fluorescence at $3,370 while the other is Faint Blue at $3,280, choose the Faint Blue — $90 saved for zero additional risk. If one is Medium Blue at $3,150, watch the video for both and choose the cleaner one.

### Does fluorescence affect the resale value of a diamond?

Yes, by approximately the same discount percentage as at original purchase. A Strong Blue fluorescence stone purchased at a 10% discount vs None will resell at approximately a 10% discount vs comparable None stones. The discount is consistent across the market. It is not an additional penalty on resale beyond what was already priced in at purchase.

### What is the "blue haze" phenomenon exactly?

Blue haze is the visible milkiness or blue-white cast that appears in a small percentage of Very Strong Blue fluorescence diamonds when viewed under UV-rich lighting. The diamond appears foggy or over-bright, as if looking through a slightly cloudy glass. This is caused by excessive UV emission intensity overwhelming the stone's normal optical dispersion. It is most visible in direct outdoor sunlight at midday and under jewellery store UV-rich spotlighting. It is invisible under modern indoor LED.

### Is fluorescence in the GIA report always accurate?

Yes. GIA grades fluorescence under standardised UV light sources with strict calibration. The fluorescence grade on the GIA certificate is accurate and consistent. Independent testing by industry researchers has confirmed GIA fluorescence grading to be highly reliable across thousands of stones.

### Should I worry about fluorescence when buying a lab diamond at $1,950?

Not significantly. At the [lab 1.5ct D-VVS1 Excellent Cut](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28629934?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) price tier (~$1,950), the primary concern is cut proportions and video performance. Fluorescence is a secondary consideration. If the stone has Strong or Very Strong fluorescence, check the video for haze; if clean, accept it — the pricing at this tier already reflects the lab-grown discount.

